The aim to change something occurred as the peak of discontent with the functioning of democratic institutions and no definition of “we want something different”. The main charm of the opposition has been its visibility. The opposition has been more popular than the government, so as a government you know you can’t go on as you are before, said Professor of Political Science, Paneuria Foundation Executive Director Dimitri Shashkin in the conversation with CABAR.asia.

CABAR.asia: Mr. Shashkin, in October, Georgia began to defend itself from the coronavirus, which as a threat to civilians is contrary to our previous conclusions that have nothing to do with hospitals, health care. What do you think of such an experience? After many months of quarantine, more than 130 thousand people in Georgia were sick, more than 1,000 deaths. Most curious: where do the small outbreaks come from? And how the BVL-2 virus prevention and laboratory testing work?

Mr. Dimitri Shashkin: I think that vaccination will be introduced in Georgia very soon. How grateful the experts are talking about the new strains including new mutations of coronavirus. It seems like the race with new strains of the enemy is on the full, and the vaccine is ahead of the new strains. Because the vaccine just manages to develop with new strains of viruses.
